
[1]commendam

   COMMENDAM, n. In ecclesiastical law, in England, a benefice or living
   commended, by the king or head of the church, to the care of a clerk,
   to hold till a proper pastor is provided. This may be temporary or
   perpetual.

   The trust or administration of the revenues of a benefice given to a
   layman, to hold as a deposit for six months in order to repairs, &c.,
   or to an ecclesiastic, to perform the pastoral duties, till the
   benefice is provided with a regular incumbent.
